# ============================================================================
# NOTES & BEST PRACTICES
# ============================================================================
#
# Environment-Specific Files:
# ===========================
# Consider using environment-specific .env files:
# - .env.development (local development)
# - .env.staging (staging environment)
# - .env.production (production - use secret manager instead!)
#
# Load with: export $(cat .env.development | xargs)
# Or use tools like direnv (https://direnv.net/)
#
#
# Secret Management Services:
# ============================
# For production, use dedicated secret management services:
#
# AWS Secrets Manager:
#   - Store secrets in AWS Secrets Manager
#   - Access via AWS SDK or environment variables
#   - Automatic rotation support
#   - IAM-based access control
#
# HashiCorp Vault:
#   - Enterprise-grade secret management
#   - Dynamic secrets generation
#   - Audit logging
#   - Multi-cloud support
#
# Azure Key Vault:
#   - Azure-native secret storage
#   - Integration with Azure services
#   - Access policies and RBAC
#
# Google Secret Manager:
#   - GCP-native secret storage
#   - Versioning and rotation
#   - IAM integration
#
#
# Security Best Practices:
# ========================
# 1. Never commit .env files to version control
# 2. Use strong, unique SECRET_KEY (64+ characters)
# 3. Rotate secrets regularly (every 90 days)
# 4. Use different credentials for each environment
# 5. Limit access to production secrets (principle of least privilege)
# 6. Use secret management services in production
# 7. Enable MFA for all service accounts
# 8. Monitor for exposed secrets (GitHub secret scanning, etc.)
# 9. Use environment variables over hardcoded values
# 10. Encrypt secrets at rest and in transit
#
#
# Development vs Production:
# ==========================
# Development:
#   - Use SQLite (no setup required)
#   - DEBUG=true for detailed errors
#   - Local LLM or development API keys
#   - Relaxed CORS (* for localhost)
#
# Production:
#   - Use PostgreSQL (scalable, reliable)
#   - DEBUG=false (security)
#   - Production API keys with rate limits
#   - Strict CORS (specific domains only)
#   - Use secret management service
#   - Enable monitoring (Sentry, etc.)
#   - Use SSL/TLS for all connections
#
#
# Troubleshooting:
# ================
# - If database connection fails: Check DATABASE_URL format
# - If JWT tokens invalid: Verify SECRET_KEY is set correctly
# - If LLM calls fail: Check API keys and base URLs
# - If email not sending: Verify SMTP credentials and port
# - Check logs: Set LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG for detailed information
#
# ============================================================================

